tska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"ABT1162–":"okolo 1162–Zesnulý","1162–Male":"1162–Zesnulý","1210–Male":"1210–Zesnulý","1131–Male":"1131–Zesnulý","ABT1162":"okolo 1162","1210":"1210","1131":"1131","1162":"1162","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotsko, United Kingdom"},"da":{"ABT1162–":"omkring 1162–Afdød","1162–Male":"1162–Afdød","1210–Male":"1210–Afdød","1131–Male":"1131–Afdød","ABT1162":"omkring 1162","1210":"1210","1131":"1131","1162":"1162","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"ABT1162–":"circa 1162–Overleden","1162–Male":"1162–Overleden","1210–Male":"1210–Overleden","1131–Male":"1131–Overleden","ABT1162":"circa 1162","1210":"1210","1131":"1131","1162":"1162","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT1162–":"about 1162–Deceased","1162–Male":"1162–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1131–Male":"1131–Deceased","ABT1162":"about 1162","1210":"1210","1131":"1131","1162":"1162","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Abrahamm","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Dutch, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name   Abraham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abraham","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Mathai, Mohan, Raju, Saji, Prasad, Anil, Babu, Biju, Leela, Sajan, Shibu, Suma.","English, French, Spanish, German, Slovenian, Ethiopian, and Assyrian/Chaldean; Hungarian (<b>Ábrahám</b>), Slovak (mainly <b>Abrahám</b>, also <b>Ábrahám</b>), Czech (also <b>Abrahám</b>): from the Hebrew personal name <i>ʾAbraham</i> (modern spelling <i>Avraham</i>), borne by the Biblical patriarch revered by Jews as the founding father of the Jewish people (Genesis 11–25) and by Muslims as founder of all the Semitic peoples, both Hebrew and Arab (compare   Ibrahim  ). The original name of the Biblical patriarch was probably   Abram  , meaning ‘high father’ (from <i>ab</i> father, <i>ram</i> ‘exalted’), while its later form is explained in Genesis 17:5 as being derived from Hebrew <i>ab hamon goyim</i> ‘father of a multitude of nations’. It was widely used as a personal name among Christians as well as Jews in the Middle Ages. The name <i>Abraham</i> is also found among Christians in southern India, but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. As a surname of Hungarian origin <i>Abraham</i> is also found in Romania. — Note: Since Ethiopians do not have hereditary surnames, the Ethiopian name was registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as an equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’. See   McBroom   and compare   Breheny  ."]}]},{"name":"Sarai","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sarai Abrahamm was born about 1162, in Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Gwen Scoules. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT1162–":"umbes 1162–Surnud","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1131–Male":"1131–Surnud","ABT1162":"umbes 1162","1210":"1210","1131":"1131","1162":"1162","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, Un